<p><a name="References" id="References"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Military_strategy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: References">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">References</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Gartner, Scott Sigmund, <i>Strategic Assessment in War</i>, Yale University Press, 1999</li>
<li>Matloff, Maurice, (ed.), <i>American Military History: 1775-1902, volume 1</i>, Combined Books, 1996</li>
<li>Chaliand, Gérard, <i>The Art of War in World History: From Antiquity to the Nuclear Age</i>, University of California Press, 1994</li>
<li>Wilden, Anthony, <i>Man and Woman, War and Peace: The Strategist's Companion</i>, Routledge, 1987</li>
<li>Carpenter, Stanley D. M., <i>Military Leadership in the British Civil Wars, 1642-1651: The Genius of This Age</i>, Routledge, 2005</li>
<li>The <a href="http://www.StrategicStudiesInstitute.army.mil" class="external text" title="http://www.StrategicStudiesInstitute.army.mil" rel="nofollow">US Army War College Strategic Studies Institute</a> publishes several dozen papers and books yearly focusing on current and future military strategy and policy, national security, and global and regional strategic issues. Most publications are relevant to the International strategic community, both academically and militarily. All are freely available to the public in PDF format. The organization was founded by General <a href="/wiki/Dwight_D._Eisenhower" title="Dwight D. Eisenhower">Dwight D. Eisenhower</a> after World War II.</li>
</ul>
